{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 15:07:47.820429", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and objective\\n- Validate end-to-end health for hosts, DNS, load balancer, and web servers across the OSPF-based enterprise topology.\\n- Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root causes (no remediation proposed).\\n\\n1) High-level health assessment\\n- Control-plane/data-plane reachability: Healthy. Multi-endpoint ping tests across user subnets and the server farm show 0% packet loss. OSPF-based connectivity appears intact.\\n- Name resolution: Healthy. DNS lookups during HTTP tests show low name-lookup times (typically 8–95 ms).\\n- Load balancer service (web99.local): Healthy and consistent. HTTP TTFB typically ~0.22–0.40 s, total times ~1.02–1.21 s from both hosts.\\n\\n2) Observed anomalies\\nA. Persistent network-induced latency and rate limitation on web_server_0 (10.200.0.3)\\n- Symptoms seen at the edge:\\n  - From host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1, ICMP RTTs to 10.200.0.3 are elevated vs peers:\\n    - host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_0: avg ~34.8 ms (vs ~5–13 ms to other servers)\\n    - host_2_1_1_1 → web_server_0: avg ~35.0 ms (vs ~5–13 ms to other servers)\\n  - HTTP to web0.local shows increased server-side delay (TTFB ~1.30–1.34 s) and longer totals (2.14–2.77 s) compared to the load balancer and other web servers in many runs.\\n\\n- Device-level findings (localized to web_server_0):\\n  - Interface configuration and qdisc:\\n    - eth0 on web_server_0 has qdisc netem with fixed delay and token-bucket shaper:\\n      - netem delay 20ms\\n      - tbf rate 1Mbit burst 500Kb\\n    - “tc -s” shows overlimits on the TBF (183), confirming active shaping.\\n  - Other web servers (web_server_1/2/3) use default fq_codel qdisc and do not show netem/tbf shaping.\\n  - Interface counters:\\n    - web_server_0 RX bytes are orders of magnitude larger than peers, indicating it is carrying significantly more traffic, and therefore any shaping/latency policy will have more visible impact.\\n\\n- Impact assessment:\\n  - The added fixed delay (20 ms) and 1 Mbit/s shaping on web_server_0 increase RTT and can inflate application response time and throughput for flows involving web0.local.\\n  - Ping/jitter patterns and the variable HTTP TTFB are consistent with queueing and serialization under a 1 Mbit/s egress shaper, especially noticeable when under load.\\n\\nRoot cause (for anomaly A): Host-level traffic control policy applied on web_server_0 eth0 (netem + TBF) causing added latency and bandwidth limitation.\\n\\nB. Intermittent elevated TTFB on some direct web servers (web1.local, web2.local, web3.local)\\n- HTTP tests sometimes show TTFB spikes around ~1.22–1.33 s on these servers, alternating with normal values (~0.25–0.35 s).\\n- Network path indicators (ICMP RTT to 10.200.0.4–.6) remain low once ARP is resolved (1–3 ms typical), with no loss.\\n- This pattern suggests application stack or server-side processing variability rather than a network delivery issue. No network queueing/shaping found on these hosts.\\n\\nRoot cause hypothesis (for anomaly B): Intermittent application-side latency on individual web servers. Not attributable to network fabric based on RTT/loss and absence of host-level shaping on those servers.\\n\\n3) Additional relevant findings\\n- Load balancer service to hosts is stable and performant compared to direct access to web_server_0, indicating balanced path and upstream routing are functioning normally.\\n- DNS service is responsive with low lookup times during HTTP testing.\\n- OSPF fabric (core, distribution, and server access) supports end-to-end reachability; tests show consistent, lossless connectivity across areas.\\n\\n4) Fault localization summary\\n- Faulty device conclusively identified: web_server_0 (host 10.200.0.3).\\n- Faulty component: eth0 qdisc configuration (netem 20ms delay + TBF 1 Mbit/s).\\n- Effect: Elevated RTT, increased HTTP TTFB and reduced throughput to web0.local relative to other services.\\n- The rest of the network (routers, switches, DNS, load balancer, other web servers) shows no evidence of packet loss or systemic routing issues.\\n\\n5) Overall status\\n- Network core/distribution/server access routing: Normal.\\n- DNS: Normal.\\n- Load balancer (web99.local): Normal.\\n- Direct web servers:\\n  - web_server_0: Abnormal due to host-level QoS shaping and induced delay (root cause identified).\\n  - web_server_1/2/3: Reachable; occasional TTFB spikes likely application-related, not network-induced., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bdfe48ec-f3fb-4ee0-9b2e-723b8f5c60fb'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
